WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.140 --> 00:00:03.830
Welcome to Jeremy’s IT Lab.

00:00:03.830 --> 00:00:09.470
This is a complete course for the CCNA, including
everything you need to pass the exam, all

00:00:09.470 --> 00:00:11.990
100% free.

00:00:11.990 --> 00:00:15.740
Make sure you stay tuned till the end of the
video for the quiz to test your knowledge

00:00:15.740 --> 00:00:18.240
of the material in this video.

00:00:18.240 --> 00:00:23.900
Also, remember to download and use the Anki
flashcards with the link in the description,

00:00:23.900 --> 00:00:26.359
which will help you very much in your studies.

00:00:26.359 --> 00:00:29.119
Let’s get started.

00:00:29.119 --> 00:00:35.320
In this fourth lesson, we will finally get
started actually configuring some Cisco devices.

00:00:35.320 --> 00:00:39.500
This lesson is about the Cisco IOS CLI.

00:00:39.500 --> 00:00:46.629
Cisco IOS is the operating system used on
Cisco devices, like Windows on a PC, or macOS

00:00:46.629 --> 00:00:47.629
on an imac.

00:00:47.629 --> 00:00:54.199
Keep in mind, Cisco’s IOS is not related
to Apple’s iOS for iPhones.

00:00:54.199 --> 00:00:57.629
Now, what is a CLI?

00:00:57.629 --> 00:01:01.079
CLI stands for command-line interface.

00:01:01.079 --> 00:01:07.630
It’s the interface you use to configure
Cisco devices, like routers, switches, and

00:01:07.630 --> 00:01:08.630
firewalls.

00:01:08.630 --> 00:01:12.729
Here’s an image of the Cisco IOS CLI.

00:01:12.729 --> 00:01:16.790
The color scheme can be changed, this is just
the default color scheme with the software

00:01:16.790 --> 00:01:19.280
I used when taking this screenshot.

00:01:19.280 --> 00:01:25.229
Now, there is also something called a GUI,
which means graphical user interface.

00:01:25.229 --> 00:01:32.860
Here’s an example of a Cisco GUI, from Cisco’s
ASDM which can be used to configure Cisco's firewalls.

00:01:32.860 --> 00:01:39.520
However, we won’t cover GUIs in this course,
and most network engineers prefer to use the

00:01:39.520 --> 00:01:42.840
CLI over a GUI.

00:01:42.840 --> 00:01:48.770
Now, how exactly do you connect to a Cisco
device to configure it with the CLI?

00:01:48.770 --> 00:01:54.869
There are a couple methods, but I’m going
to talk about connecting via the console port.

00:01:54.869 --> 00:01:58.680
Connecting to a device via the console port
typically involves bringing your laptop to

00:01:58.680 --> 00:02:03.649
the device and connecting to the console port
of the device.

00:02:03.649 --> 00:02:07.930
There are also methods to connect to a device
remotely, but we’ll cover that later.

00:02:07.930 --> 00:02:15.150
In any case, when you first configure a device,
you have to connect to the console port.

00:02:15.150 --> 00:02:21.879
This is an image of a Cisco catalyst switch,
and notice the two console ports.

00:02:21.879 --> 00:02:27.110
one of them is an RJ45 port, just like the
switch’s network ports.

00:02:27.110 --> 00:02:31.180
The other is a USB mini-b connector.

00:02:31.180 --> 00:02:36.190
You can connect to either of these, but let’s
say we’re going to connect to the RJ45 port.

00:02:36.190 --> 00:02:39.930
You’re going to need the proper cable.

00:02:39.930 --> 00:02:42.650
This is the kind of cable you will use.

00:02:42.650 --> 00:02:49.090
Notice one end has an RJ45 connector, just
like the Ethernet UTP cables we looked at.

00:02:49.090 --> 00:02:52.110
The other end is a DB9 connector.

00:02:52.110 --> 00:02:57.879
However, most laptops these days no longer
have a serial port to plug the cable into,

00:02:57.879 --> 00:03:05.069
so you’ll probably need an adapter, like
this, to connect to a USB port on your laptop.

00:03:05.069 --> 00:03:09.459
The actual name of the cable on the left is
‘rollover cable’.

00:03:09.459 --> 00:03:14.130
The name is similar to a crossover cable,
but it’s different than an Ethernet UTP

00:03:14.130 --> 00:03:16.430
crossover cable.

00:03:16.430 --> 00:03:21.190
Like in an Ethernet UTP cable, there are 8
pins on each end that are used.

00:03:21.190 --> 00:03:32.580
However, they connect like this: pin 1 to
pin 8, pin 2 to pin 7, pin 3 to pin 6, pin 4 to

00:03:32.580 --> 00:03:43.780
pin 5, pin 5 to pin 4, pin 6 to pin 3, pin 7 to
pin 2, and pin 8 to pin 1.

00:03:43.780 --> 00:03:49.260
So, once you’ve connected your computer
to the device, how do you actually access

00:03:49.260 --> 00:03:50.299
the CLI?

00:03:50.299 --> 00:03:57.549
Well, you need to use a terminal emulator,
this one here, PuTTy, is a popular choice.

00:03:57.549 --> 00:04:04.489
You can get it at putty.org. select serial,
here, and then click open and you should be

00:04:04.489 --> 00:04:07.360
connected to the CLI.

00:04:07.360 --> 00:04:13.200
You should be able to connect with the default
settings, but click serial down here, and

00:04:13.200 --> 00:04:17.770
you can view and edit the default settings
for the serial connection.

00:04:17.770 --> 00:04:22.020
Note that these settings match the defaults
on Cisco devices, so you’ll probably never

00:04:22.020 --> 00:04:26.040
have to change them, but it’s good to be
aware of them, and try to remember them for

00:04:26.040 --> 00:04:28.160
the test.

00:04:28.160 --> 00:04:34.640
The speed, also known as baud rate, is 9,600
bits per second.

00:04:34.640 --> 00:04:39.890
there are 8 data bits, and 1 stop bit.

00:04:39.890 --> 00:04:44.800
Understanding data bits and stop bits is
outside of the scope of the CCNA, but basically

00:04:44.800 --> 00:04:51.210
it means that for each 8 bits of data one
stop bit is sent, to mark the end of the 8

00:04:51.210 --> 00:04:52.210
bits.

00:04:52.210 --> 00:04:54.230
Parity is set to none.

00:04:54.230 --> 00:04:56.680
Parity is used to detect errors.

00:04:56.680 --> 00:05:00.460
And finally, flow control is set to none.

00:05:00.460 --> 00:05:04.390
Flow control is exactly what it sounds like,
controlling the flow of data from transmitter

00:05:04.390 --> 00:05:09.430
to receiver, but again you don’t have to
worry about the details for the exam.

00:05:09.430 --> 00:05:11.920
Just remember Cisco’s defaults.

00:05:11.920 --> 00:05:21.300
Speed of 9600 bits per second, 8 data bits,
1 stop bit, no parity, and no flow control.

00:05:21.300 --> 00:05:27.630
Once you connect to the device, you will be
greeted with a screen like this.

00:05:27.630 --> 00:05:31.800
Since this is the first time booting up the
device, I am asked if I would like to enter

00:05:31.800 --> 00:05:36.570
the initial configuration dialog, and I answer
no.

00:05:36.570 --> 00:05:40.780
Then I pressed the enter key to get started,
and I’m now free to type commands into the

00:05:40.780 --> 00:05:43.440
CLI.

00:05:43.440 --> 00:05:48.391
When you first enter the CLI, you will by
default be in what’s called ‘user EXEC

00:05:48.391 --> 00:05:50.250
mode’.

00:05:50.250 --> 00:05:54.740
User EXEC mode is indicated by the ‘greater
than sign’ next to the host name of the

00:05:54.740 --> 00:05:56.880
device.

00:05:56.880 --> 00:06:01.310
Note that the default host name for this device
is ‘Router’.

00:06:01.310 --> 00:06:06.060
The text displayed here always indicates the
hostname of the device.

00:06:06.060 --> 00:06:12.870
All devices have a hostname, and for a Cisco
router the default name is Router.

00:06:12.870 --> 00:06:15.930
User exec mode is very limited.

00:06:15.930 --> 00:06:21.590
Users can look at some things, but can’t
make any changes to the configuration.

00:06:21.590 --> 00:06:24.520
Usually you don’t do anything in this mode.

00:06:24.520 --> 00:06:27.180
You also might hear it called just ‘user
mode’.

00:06:27.180 --> 00:06:33.380
So, let’s move to a mode with a little more
power to make changes to the device.

00:06:33.380 --> 00:06:38.370
If you enter the ‘enable’ command in user
EXEC mode, you will be placed in privileged

00:06:38.370 --> 00:06:40.280
exec mode.

00:06:40.280 --> 00:06:44.960
In privileged exec mode, a pound sign, or
hashtag, whatever you want to call it, is

00:06:44.960 --> 00:06:47.370
displayed.

00:06:47.370 --> 00:06:52.130
Privileged EXEC mode provides complete access
to view the device’s configuration, restart

00:06:52.130 --> 00:06:55.020
the device, etc.

00:06:55.020 --> 00:06:59.310
This is not the mode in which you actually
change the configuration, however you can

00:06:59.310 --> 00:07:04.600
change the time on the device, and also save
the current configuration file, among many other

00:07:04.600 --> 00:07:06.880
things.

00:07:06.880 --> 00:07:12.620
This is a comparison of the commands available
in user EXEC mode, on the left, and privileged

00:07:12.620 --> 00:07:14.090
EXEC mode, on the right.

00:07:14.090 --> 00:07:20.130
Also, I’m taking these screenshots from
Cisco Packet Tracer software.

00:07:20.130 --> 00:07:22.770
Packet tracer is a network simulator.

00:07:22.770 --> 00:07:28.560
It is a fantastic resource for the CCNA, but
it is limited beyond the CCNA.

00:07:28.560 --> 00:07:32.650
There are many things which Packet Tracer
doesn’t support, so if I were to show these

00:07:32.650 --> 00:07:38.530
commands on a real device, you would probably
see even more commands available here.

00:07:38.530 --> 00:07:43.400
I want to repeat, however, that Packet tracer
is an excellent resource for the CCNA and

00:07:43.400 --> 00:07:47.380
you don’t really need to use anything else for
your CCNA.

00:07:47.380 --> 00:07:52.580
One more thing, notice the command I used
to view the available commands.

00:07:52.580 --> 00:07:58.630
You can use a question mark to view the commands
that are available to you.

00:07:58.630 --> 00:08:02.140
Now I want to show you a convenient feature
of the CLI.

00:08:02.140 --> 00:08:04.530
That is the tab key.

00:08:04.530 --> 00:08:11.470
In the sample output here, notice the first
line says en, the second says enable, and

00:08:11.470 --> 00:08:13.550
then I entered privileged exec mode.

00:08:13.550 --> 00:08:20.110
Well, if you press tab, the CLI will automatically
complete the word for you, and display the

00:08:20.110 --> 00:08:22.390
complete word on a new line.

00:08:22.390 --> 00:08:28.340
However, another convenient thing is that
you don’t even need to complete the command.

00:08:28.340 --> 00:08:34.820
Here I just typed ‘en’, and hit enter,
and I was brought to privileged EXEC mode.

00:08:34.820 --> 00:08:39.660
This can really save you a lot of typing when
you’re entering many commands.

00:08:39.660 --> 00:08:41.940
There are limits to this, however.

00:08:41.940 --> 00:08:46.000
Although ‘en’ was enough for the router
to understand that I meant to use the command

00:08:46.000 --> 00:08:50.640
‘enable’, that’s because it’s the
only command that begins with EN that can

00:08:50.640 --> 00:08:53.580
be entered in user EXEC mode.

00:08:53.580 --> 00:08:58.750
If I type just ‘e’, however, we are told
that it is an ambiguous command.

00:08:58.750 --> 00:09:03.780
That’s because there’s more than one command
that begins with e.

00:09:03.780 --> 00:09:07.050
How can we view the commands that begin with
e?

00:09:07.050 --> 00:09:09.280
Well, remember the question mark from before?

00:09:09.280 --> 00:09:14.340
If I type e, followed by a question mark,
it displays the possible commands that begin

00:09:14.340 --> 00:09:16.050
with e.

00:09:16.050 --> 00:09:23.370
There are two, enable and exit, so if I type just ‘e’ and hit enter, the router doesn’t

00:09:23.370 --> 00:09:25.470
know which command I want to use.

00:09:25.470 --> 00:09:29.230
So, the shortest form of the enable command
is ‘en’.

00:09:29.230 --> 00:09:35.140
And, the shortest form of the exit command
is ‘ex’.

00:09:35.140 --> 00:09:39.270
Now let’s actually make some changes to
the router’s configuration.

00:09:39.270 --> 00:09:43.670
To do so, we enter ‘global configuration mode’.

00:09:43.670 --> 00:09:48.870
The command to enter configuration mode is
configure terminal.

00:09:48.870 --> 00:09:54.840
When in global configuration mode, config is inserted
after the hostname.

00:09:54.840 --> 00:09:58.470
Once again, you don’t have to type the whole
word.

00:09:58.470 --> 00:10:03.181
Notice I type con, followed by the question
mark, and there are two options, configure

00:10:03.181 --> 00:10:04.590
and connect.

00:10:04.590 --> 00:10:10.120
So, the shortest possible command for configure
is conf, c-o-n-f.

00:10:10.120 --> 00:10:18.060
However, terminal is the only option beginning
with T, so all I need to type is CONF T to

00:10:18.060 --> 00:10:21.090
enter global configuration mode.

00:10:21.090 --> 00:10:26.270
From now on, in all of my lab demonstrations
and such, I will probably be typing conf t

00:10:26.270 --> 00:10:29.490
instead of configure terminal.

00:10:29.490 --> 00:10:35.570
Try to remember that the full command is configure
terminal, but also feel free to use the shortcuts.

00:10:35.570 --> 00:10:41.560
Now, we don’t want just anyone to be able
to make changes to the network configuration,

00:10:41.560 --> 00:10:47.180
or even be able to just look at the configuration,
because that could be a security risk.

00:10:47.180 --> 00:10:52.170
We can protect privileged exec mode with a
password, so that if a user enters the ‘enable’

00:10:52.170 --> 00:10:57.160
command from user EXEC mode, they are asked
for the password.

00:10:57.160 --> 00:11:02.170
That is done with the command ‘enable password’
in global configuration mode.

00:11:02.170 --> 00:11:07.070
First, I want to clarify the use of the question
mark.

00:11:07.070 --> 00:11:11.070
Notice that I used the question mark with
no space after password.

00:11:11.070 --> 00:11:13.040
here is the output.

00:11:13.040 --> 00:11:18.050
If you use the question mark with no space,
it shows you all possible completions of that

00:11:18.050 --> 00:11:19.050
word.

00:11:19.050 --> 00:11:24.240
I already typed the full word password, so
it just displays the word again, and there

00:11:24.240 --> 00:11:30.700
are no other words that begin with p-a-s-s-w-o-r-d.

00:11:30.700 --> 00:11:35.940
Next I used the question mark again, this
time with a space after password.

00:11:35.940 --> 00:11:38.630
Notice the difference in the output.

00:11:38.630 --> 00:11:43.590
This time it shows all possible options we
could enter next in the command.

00:11:43.590 --> 00:11:46.790
In this case, I used the middle one.

00:11:46.790 --> 00:11:50.570
Notice that LINE is in all capital letters.

00:11:50.570 --> 00:11:55.960
That means that you don’t actually type
LINE, you type a line which will become the

00:11:55.960 --> 00:11:57.740
password.

00:11:57.740 --> 00:12:02.700
I typed CCNA in all capitals as the password.

00:12:02.700 --> 00:12:10.120
Note that Password ARE case-sensitive, so
CCNA in capital letters and ccna in lower-case

00:12:10.120 --> 00:12:13.650
letters are different passwords.

00:12:13.650 --> 00:12:17.330
Once again I typed the question mark to check
if there are any further options.

00:12:17.330 --> 00:12:23.320
This cr means that there are no further options,
the only option is to press enter to enter

00:12:23.320 --> 00:12:24.460
the command.

00:12:24.460 --> 00:12:27.600
I pressed enter, and now the password is set.

00:12:27.600 --> 00:12:28.860
Let’s test it.

00:12:28.860 --> 00:12:32.620
So, let’s test out our password.

00:12:32.620 --> 00:12:39.110
I type exit to return to privileged EXEC mode.
from privileged exec mode, if I type exit

00:12:39.110 --> 00:12:44.060
again I am logged out of the device and see
the starting screen again.

00:12:44.060 --> 00:12:45.130
If I press enter here

00:12:45.130 --> 00:12:50.050
I am brought back to user exec mode.

00:12:50.050 --> 00:12:54.690
If I enter the enable command, I am asked
for a password.

00:12:54.690 --> 00:12:58.630
No password displays here, but I am brought
to privileged exec mode.

00:12:58.630 --> 00:13:04.250
That’s because the password does not display
as you type it, for security purposes.

00:13:04.250 --> 00:13:10.510
Also, note that if you enter the wrong password
3 times , you will be denied access for having

00:13:10.510 --> 00:13:12.110
‘bad secrets’.

00:13:12.110 --> 00:13:17.930
I think everyone has bad secrets of some kind,
but in this case it means an incorrect password.

00:13:17.930 --> 00:13:22.800
Let’s review what we’ve done so far.

00:13:22.800 --> 00:13:27.190
In my experience it was difficult to get used
to operating in the CLI when I first started

00:13:27.190 --> 00:13:31.370
learning, so we’ll take it slow and review
along the way.

00:13:31.370 --> 00:13:36.880
Also, make sure to check out the next video after you finish this,
which will have you doing these same tasks

00:13:36.880 --> 00:13:39.050
in packet tracer.

00:13:39.050 --> 00:13:43.150
Hands-on practice is absolutely essential
to get comfortable with the CLI.

00:13:43.150 --> 00:13:48.740
So, I use the enable command to enter privileged
exec mode.

00:13:48.740 --> 00:13:53.300
From privileged exec mode, I use configure
terminal to enter global configuration

00:13:53.300 --> 00:13:55.020
mode.

00:13:55.020 --> 00:14:01.560
In global configuration mode, I use the command
enable password CCNA to protect privileged

00:14:01.560 --> 00:14:03.410
exec mode with a password.

00:14:03.410 --> 00:14:08.230
Remember, this password is case-sensitive.

00:14:08.230 --> 00:14:12.190
Then I type exit to return to privileged exec
mode.

00:14:12.190 --> 00:14:15.779
And exit again to return to user exec mode.

00:14:15.779 --> 00:14:18.060
I type enable again.

00:14:18.060 --> 00:14:23.880
then I enter the password, which isn’t displayed
as I type it, and I am brought back into privileged

00:14:23.880 --> 00:14:26.460
EXEC mode.

00:14:26.460 --> 00:14:30.310
We confirmed the function of the password,
but let’s take a look at the configuration

00:14:30.310 --> 00:14:33.529
file itself to check it.

00:14:33.529 --> 00:14:38.220
First I want to explain the two configuration
files kept on the device.

00:14:38.220 --> 00:14:43.500
As I said, there are two separate configuration
files kept on the device at once.

00:14:43.500 --> 00:14:46.130
One is the running-config.

00:14:46.130 --> 00:14:50.590
This is the current, active configuration
file on the device.

00:14:50.590 --> 00:14:56.210
As you enter commands in the CLI, you edit
the active configuration.

00:14:56.210 --> 00:15:02.640
The startup-config is the configuration file
that will be loaded upon restart of the device.

00:15:02.640 --> 00:15:07.920
If you reload the device, or shut it
down and then turn it on later, the startup-config

00:15:07.920 --> 00:15:10.320
will be loaded.

00:15:10.320 --> 00:15:14.300
So let’s take a look at the configuration
files.

00:15:14.300 --> 00:15:19.290
Use the ‘show running-config’ command
in global configuration mode to view the running

00:15:19.290 --> 00:15:21.779
configuration file.

00:15:21.779 --> 00:15:26.221
There is lots of data in the file by default,
so I only included the output up to the command

00:15:26.221 --> 00:15:27.260
we entered.

00:15:27.260 --> 00:15:33.880
Here’s the command, enable password CCNA,
in the running-config.

00:15:33.880 --> 00:15:36.339
How about the startup-config?

00:15:36.339 --> 00:15:42.180
You can view it with the show startup-config
command, however as you can see, at this point

00:15:42.180 --> 00:15:46.820
it just displays the message ‘startup-config
is not present’.

00:15:46.820 --> 00:15:51.680
This is because we haven’t saved the running
configuration yet, so every time we restart

00:15:51.680 --> 00:15:55.880
the router it will load a default configuration,
not the startup-configuration.

00:15:55.880 --> 00:16:00.990
Let’s save the configuration file.

00:16:00.990 --> 00:16:05.090
There are actually three ways you can save
the running-configuration, to make it the

00:16:05.090 --> 00:16:07.339
startup-configuration.

00:16:07.339 --> 00:16:11.830
All three of these commands are executed from
privileged exec mode.

00:16:11.830 --> 00:16:13.920
The first is ‘write’.

00:16:13.920 --> 00:16:18.800
It says building configuration, and then an
OK message to indicate that the configuration

00:16:18.800 --> 00:16:20.820
was saved.

00:16:20.820 --> 00:16:25.990
The second method is write memory, it performs
the same function.

00:16:25.990 --> 00:16:30.790
The third command is copy running-config startup-config.

00:16:30.790 --> 00:16:36.620
This tells the router to copy the running-config
file to the startup-config file, again performing

00:16:36.620 --> 00:16:40.310
the same function as the previous two commands.

00:16:40.310 --> 00:16:45.180
Now if I use the show startup-config command
again, it displays the same configuration

00:16:45.180 --> 00:16:48.870
as the show running-config command.

00:16:48.870 --> 00:16:53.660
Once again, however, this is only the beginning
of the output, there is more below.

00:16:53.660 --> 00:16:58.529
We’ll check it out in the packet tracer
lab video coming up next.

00:16:58.529 --> 00:17:03.850
Now, you can see the enable password right
here, in plain text.

00:17:03.850 --> 00:17:09.350
This is a security risk, because anyone who
simply takes a glance at this password knows

00:17:09.350 --> 00:17:13.990
how to get into privileged exec mode, and
then global configuration mode to make changes

00:17:13.990 --> 00:17:14.990
to the device.

00:17:14.990 --> 00:17:18.929
Let’s level up the security a bit.

00:17:18.929 --> 00:17:26.150
You can do so with the ‘service password-encryption’
command in global configuration mode.

00:17:26.150 --> 00:17:31.240
Notice I used the short version of configure
terminal, conf t, to enter global configuration

00:17:31.240 --> 00:17:33.179
mode.

00:17:33.179 --> 00:17:35.860
Remember that all of these commands have shortcuts.

00:17:35.860 --> 00:17:41.360
I’ll usually use the full command for these
instructional videos, but in the labs

00:17:41.360 --> 00:17:45.680
when I enter the commands live you’ll see
me using the shortcuts a lot.

00:17:45.680 --> 00:17:51.270
Anyway, the service password-encryption command
will encrypt all passwords in a jumble of

00:17:51.270 --> 00:17:55.850
numbers and letters, so that they cannot be
easily read.

00:17:55.850 --> 00:18:01.230
If I enter the show running-config command
again, notice that the password ‘CCNA’

00:18:01.230 --> 00:18:06.620
has become 08026F6028.

00:18:06.620 --> 00:18:12.059
The password itself hasn’t changed, it is
still CCNA, only the way it is displayed in

00:18:12.059 --> 00:18:14.590
the configuration has changed.

00:18:14.590 --> 00:18:19.730
Also, you may notice that a 7 has appeared
before the password.

00:18:19.730 --> 00:18:25.060
This number ‘7’ indicates the type of
encryption used to encrypt the password.

00:18:25.060 --> 00:18:30.910
The number 7 means it is using Cisco’s proprietary
encryption algorithm, from the service password-encryption

00:18:30.910 --> 00:18:36.970
command. 
 Later in this video you will see another number
in that place.

00:18:36.970 --> 00:18:42.470
While using the ‘service password-encryption’
command is more secure than not using it,

00:18:42.470 --> 00:18:45.500
it’s still not very secure.

00:18:45.500 --> 00:18:51.520
In this screenshot I simply searched for a
cisco type 7 password cracker on google, found

00:18:51.520 --> 00:18:57.240
this website, and was able to crack the password
in a few seconds.

00:18:57.240 --> 00:19:01.170
The good news, though, is that there is a
more secure enable password that can be used

00:19:01.170 --> 00:19:05.880
on Cisco devices, with a tougher type of encryption.

00:19:05.880 --> 00:19:11.600
The more secure method is to use the enable
secret command, instead of the enable password

00:19:11.600 --> 00:19:13.250
command.

00:19:13.250 --> 00:19:21.000
This time I used a password of Cisco, with
an upper-case C. Once again, this is case-sensitive.

00:19:21.000 --> 00:19:24.270
Then I view the running configuration once
more.

00:19:24.270 --> 00:19:31.540
However, since I was still in global configuration
mode, I typed ‘do’ in front of the command.

00:19:31.540 --> 00:19:35.760
This is a convenient trick that allows you
to execute privileged exec mode commands like

00:19:35.760 --> 00:19:42.370
show running-config or show startup-config,
in other configuration levels.

00:19:42.370 --> 00:19:51.030
Also notice I used shortcuts, sh instead of
show, and run instead of running-config.

00:19:51.030 --> 00:19:55.120
Now you can see the enable secret in the running-configuration.

00:19:55.120 --> 00:19:59.010
Notice the number 5 before the encrypted password.

00:19:59.010 --> 00:20:04.170
Number 5 indicates MD5 type encryption, which
is much more secure than what we got with

00:20:04.170 --> 00:20:07.480
the service password-encryption command.

00:20:07.480 --> 00:20:13.210
It can still be cracked, no password is invincible,
but its much better.

00:20:13.210 --> 00:20:18.370
Also notice that the enable password command
remains, it isn’t replaced.

00:20:18.370 --> 00:20:24.100
However, if both the enable secret and enable
password commands are configured, the enable

00:20:24.100 --> 00:20:29.520
password will be ignored, only the enable
secret will be valid.

00:20:29.520 --> 00:20:35.080
One final note, the ‘service password-encryption’
command has NO effect on the enable secret

00:20:35.080 --> 00:20:36.770
command.

00:20:36.770 --> 00:20:41.620
The enable secret is always encrypted, whether
or not you entered the service password-encryption

00:20:41.620 --> 00:20:42.620
command.

00:20:42.620 --> 00:20:47.771
So, really you should always use the enable
secret, instead of the enable password, as

00:20:47.771 --> 00:20:51.280
it is more secure.

00:20:51.280 --> 00:20:56.290
Now I want to show you one more thing in the
CLI before we move on to the quiz for today’s

00:20:56.290 --> 00:20:57.290
video.

00:20:57.290 --> 00:21:02.320
That is, how you cancel, or delete, a command
that you entered.

00:21:02.320 --> 00:21:06.710
That is done by typing ‘no’ in front of
the command.

00:21:06.710 --> 00:21:12.390
For example, if I type ‘no’ in front of
the service password encryption command, future

00:21:12.390 --> 00:21:14.980
passwords will no longer be encrypted.

00:21:14.980 --> 00:21:21.640
However, as you can see here, passwords which
are already encrypted will NOT be decrypted

00:21:21.640 --> 00:21:25.049
by disabling service password-encryption.

00:21:25.049 --> 00:21:30.549
If I enter a new password, however, it will
be in clear text, NOT encrypted.

00:21:30.549 --> 00:21:36.240
So, let me summarize the service-password
encryption command.

00:21:36.240 --> 00:21:43.480
If you enable service password-encryption..
current passowords will be encrypted.

00:21:43.480 --> 00:21:47.000
future passwords will also be encrypted.

00:21:47.000 --> 00:21:52.740
Once again, however, the enable secret will
not be affected, it is always encrypted.

00:21:52.740 --> 00:21:59.170
If you disable service password-encryption...
current passwords will not be decrypted, they

00:21:59.170 --> 00:22:01.960
will remain encrypted.

00:22:01.960 --> 00:22:06.830
Future passwords will not be encrypted, they
will remain in clear-text.

00:22:06.830 --> 00:22:11.840
The enable secret will not be effected, once again it
is always encrypted.

00:22:11.840 --> 00:22:16.150
Let’s review all of the commands and such
we learned in this lesson.

00:22:16.150 --> 00:22:21.390
First, the different modes of the Cisco CLI
we looked at today.

00:22:21.390 --> 00:22:27.049
First is user EXEC mode, indicated by the
greater than sign.

00:22:27.049 --> 00:22:32.850
Next is privileged exec mode, indicated by
a pound, or hashtag.

00:22:32.850 --> 00:22:40.500
Finally is global configuration mode, indicated
by config in brackets, plus the hashtag.

00:22:40.500 --> 00:22:42.720
Now let’s review some commands.

00:22:42.720 --> 00:22:47.560
The first is enable, which is used to enter
privileged exec mode.

00:22:47.560 --> 00:22:53.510
Next is configure terminal, which is used
to enter global configuration mode.

00:22:53.510 --> 00:23:00.900
Next is enable password, which configures
a password to protect privileged exec mode.

00:23:00.900 --> 00:23:06.740
The next command is service password-encryption,
which encrypts the enable password, as well

00:23:06.740 --> 00:23:09.980
as other passwords which we can configure
on the device.

00:23:09.980 --> 00:23:16.130
enable secret, which configures a
more secure enable password, which is always

00:23:16.130 --> 00:23:18.020
encrypted.

00:23:18.020 --> 00:23:24.120
Next is run (ERRATA: should be 'do'), which is used in front of a privileged
exec-level command to let you run it in global

00:23:24.130 --> 00:23:27.970
configuration mode.

00:23:27.970 --> 00:23:34.500
The next command is no, which is used to remove
a command which you previously configured.

00:23:34.500 --> 00:23:42.510
Next is show running-config, which displays
the current, active configuration file on the device.

00:23:42.510 --> 00:23:47.630
Show startup-config displays the saved configuration
file which will be loaded if the device is

00:23:47.630 --> 00:23:49.470
restarted.

00:23:49.470 --> 00:23:55.390
Okay, last three, and these are all used to
save the current running configuration and

00:23:55.390 --> 00:23:58.040
make it the startup configuration.

00:23:58.040 --> 00:24:05.720
They are… write, write memory, and copy
running-config startup-config.

00:24:05.880 --> 00:24:13.460
Okay, let’s move on to this video’s quiz,
first up, question 1.

00:24:13.470 --> 00:24:19.020
What kind of cable is used to connect to a
Cisco device via the RJ45 console port?

00:24:19.020 --> 00:24:21.950
A, rollover cable.

00:24:21.950 --> 00:24:25.610
B, crossover cable.

00:24:25.610 --> 00:24:28.919
Or C, USB cable.

00:24:28.919 --> 00:24:35.570
Pause the video to think about your answer.

00:24:35.570 --> 00:24:38.010
The answer is A , rollover cable.

00:24:38.010 --> 00:24:41.330
Let’s check the answers.

00:24:41.330 --> 00:24:49.150
A crossover cable is used to connect two devices, for example switch and switch, or router and router, or router and PC,

00:24:49.150 --> 00:24:52.650
etc.) via Ethernet.

00:24:52.650 --> 00:24:57.790
It is not used to connect to a Cisco device
via the RJ45 console port.

00:24:57.790 --> 00:25:02.070
So b, crossover cable, is incorrect.

00:25:02.070 --> 00:25:08.410
This picture shows the wiring on an Ethernet
crossover cable…

00:25:08.410 --> 00:25:13.500
Although USB cables can be used to connect
to the console of a Cisco device, the USB

00:25:13.500 --> 00:25:17.990
console port is separate from the RJ45 console
port.

00:25:17.990 --> 00:25:22.030
So c, USB cable, is incorrect.

00:25:22.030 --> 00:25:29.700
This photo shows the usb and RJ45 console
ports on a Cisco switch….

00:25:29.700 --> 00:25:35.360
A rollover cable is used to connect to the
RJ45 console port on a Cisco device.

00:25:35.360 --> 00:25:39.710
So A, rollover cable, is the correct answer.

00:25:39.710 --> 00:25:44.710
This image shows the wiring in a rollover
cable, connecting pin 1 on one side to pin

00:25:44.710 --> 00:25:51.120
8 on the other, pin 2 to pin 7, pin 3 to pin
6, etc.

00:25:51.120 --> 00:25:54.510
Let’s go to Question 2.

00:25:54.510 --> 00:25:59.870
You type enable to enter privileged exec mode
on your Cisco router, however the password

00:25:59.870 --> 00:26:02.299
you enter is not accepted.

00:26:02.299 --> 00:26:04.210
What could be the problem?

00:26:04.210 --> 00:26:08.440
A, service password-encryption is enabled.

00:26:08.440 --> 00:26:12.950
B, service password-encryption is disabled.

00:26:12.950 --> 00:26:16.400
Or C, Caps Lock is on.

00:26:16.400 --> 00:26:23.460
Pause the video to think about your answer.

00:26:23.460 --> 00:26:26.770
the answer is C, caps lock is on.

00:26:26.770 --> 00:26:29.260
Let’s check.

00:26:29.260 --> 00:26:31.850
service password-encryption is irrelevant.

00:26:31.850 --> 00:26:37.240
It doesn’t change the password itself, only
how it is displayed in the configuration.

00:26:37.240 --> 00:26:46.910
So A, service password-encryption is enabled,
and B, service password-encryption is disabled, are incorrect.

00:26:46.910 --> 00:26:51.840
Passwords are case-sensitive, so if caps lock
is on it could cause you to enter an incorrect

00:26:51.840 --> 00:26:55.950
password even if you think you’re entering
it correctly.

00:26:55.950 --> 00:26:58.940
So C, caps lock is on, is the correct answer.

00:26:58.940 --> 00:27:03.750
Let’s go to question 3.

00:27:03.750 --> 00:27:08.340
What is the most secure method to protect
access to privileged EXEC mode?

00:27:08.340 --> 00:27:11.590
A, the enable secret command.

00:27:11.590 --> 00:27:15.530
B, the enable password command.

00:27:15.530 --> 00:27:20.900
Or C, the enable password command, with service
password-encryption.

00:27:20.900 --> 00:27:26.740
Pause the video to think about your answer.

00:27:26.740 --> 00:27:29.809
The answer is A, the enable secret command.

00:27:29.809 --> 00:27:31.809
Let’s check.

00:27:31.809 --> 00:27:37.539
The enable password command configures a plain-text
password, which is not secure as it can be

00:27:37.539 --> 00:27:39.130
easily read.

00:27:39.130 --> 00:27:45.030
So B, the enable password, is incorrect.

00:27:45.030 --> 00:27:49.690
Using service password-encryption encrypts
the enable password to make it more secure,

00:27:49.690 --> 00:27:52.260
but it is a weak form of encryption.

00:27:52.260 --> 00:27:59.560
So c, enable password with service password-encryption,
is incorrect.

00:27:59.560 --> 00:28:04.110
The enable secret command configures a password
that is automatically encrypted.

00:28:04.110 --> 00:28:10.810
It uses MD5, a more secure form of encryption
than the service password-encryption command.

00:28:10.810 --> 00:28:14.430
So A, the enable secret command, is the correct
answer.

00:28:14.430 --> 00:28:18.110
Let’s go to question 4.

00:28:18.110 --> 00:28:23.059
If both the enable password and the enable
secret command are configured, what will happen

00:28:23.059 --> 00:28:27.200
when you use enable to enter privileged EXEC
mode?

00:28:27.200 --> 00:28:32.890
A, you must enter the enable password, followed
by the enable secret.

00:28:32.890 --> 00:28:37.420
B, you must enter the enable password only.

00:28:37.420 --> 00:28:41.340
Or C, you must enter the enable secret only.

00:28:41.340 --> 00:28:47.460
Pause the video to think about your answer.

00:28:47.460 --> 00:28:51.260
The answer is C, you must enter the enable
secret only.

00:28:51.260 --> 00:28:56.320
There’s not much else to explain here, the
enable secret always takes precedence over

00:28:56.320 --> 00:29:00.390
the enable password, and you’ll never be
asked to enter both.

00:29:00.390 --> 00:29:05.220
So C, you must enter the enable secret only,
is the correct answer.

00:29:05.220 --> 00:29:09.730
let’s go to the final question.

00:29:09.730 --> 00:29:14.700
You enter the conf t command to enter global
configuration mode.

00:29:14.700 --> 00:29:17.809
What is the full-length version of the command?

00:29:17.809 --> 00:29:21.190
A, configuration time.

00:29:21.190 --> 00:29:24.100
B, configure terminal.

00:29:24.100 --> 00:29:27.690
Or C, configuration terminal.

00:29:27.690 --> 00:29:33.660
Pause the video to think about your answer.

00:29:33.660 --> 00:29:36.500
The answer is B, configure terminal.

00:29:36.500 --> 00:29:40.809
Again, no special explanation is necessary
here.

00:29:40.809 --> 00:29:44.110
Even though the shortcuts are great to use
to reduce the amount of typing you have to

00:29:44.110 --> 00:29:51.679
do to enter commands, make sure you still
know the full-length versions of the commands!

